TWO security guards sent to the Passenger Rail Agency of South Africa (Prasa) in Cape Town were shot and injured by alleged cable thieves on Tuesday, 7 June. Prasa spokeswoman Nana Zenani said the shooting occurred between Bonteheuwel and Lavis Town. She said contractors were installing overhead copper cables on the line when two armed men in a black VW Polo fired 10 shots at the guards. The guards sustained gunshot wounds and are receiving treatment at a local hospital. The police are investigating the incident, and a case of attempted murder has been filed at the Elsies River Police Station,” Zenani said in a statement. ALSO READ |
Horror crash leaves 5 dead News24 reported that one guard, aged 44, was shot in both legs while another one, aged 36, was shot on his left arm and sustained bruises to the back of his head. Police spokesman Captain Frederick van Wyk said the motive of the shooting was still unknown. “Suspects fled the scene and are yet to be arrested. We urge anyone with information to contact Bishop Lavis detectives on 021 935 9820 or CrimeStop on 08600 10111,” Van Wyk said.